DEMAND AND SUPPLY
Market (collective) demand This is the
quantity of a commodity that will be bought in
the market at a given price over a given period
of time.
Specific Objectives
By the end of the topic, the teacher should be able to guide the
learner to:-
Factors influencing demand for a product
the teacher should guide the leaner in explaining the f
factors that influence demand for a product. For
example an increase in income increases demand of a
product while a decrease in income decreases demand
of a product
Derived demand and joint demand
The teacher should lead the learner in differentiating
between derived demand and joint demand using
relevant examples.
a) explain the meaning of demand
b) explain the factors which influence demand for a product
c) distinguish between derived demand and joint demand
d) derive a demand curve from a demand schedule
e) distinguish between movement along a demand curve and
shift in the demand curve
f) explain the meaning of supply
g) explain the factors that influence supply of a product
h) derive a supply curve from a supply schedule
i) distinguish between movement along a supply curve and
shift in supply curve.
j) determine equilibrium price and equilibrium quantity
k) discuss the effect of excess demand and excess supply in
the market
1) explain the effect of a shift in demand curve on
equilibrium price and equilibrium quantity.
m) explain the effect of a shift in supply curve on equilibrium
price and equilibrium quantity
n) explain other methods of determining price of a product.
Derived demand is demand for a product not for
its own sake but because it is required to
produce other goods and services. For example
machines are demanded because of the goods
they help to produce. Likewise, baking
powder is required in the production of bread
hence when the demand for bread increases,
more baking powder will be demanded and vice
versa. In this case the demand for baking
powder is derived demand.
11)
Joint demand occurs when two or more
products are demanded together. In other
words they are complimentary goods. For
example motor cars and petrol are demanded
jointly. Another example is the torches and
batteries.
a) Meaning of demand
The teacher should guide the leaner in explaining the
meaning of demand emphasizing willingness, ability,
price and time as the key elements of the definition.
In explaining demand approach it from two
perspectives:-
i) Individual demand
This is the quantity of a commodity an
individual is willing and able to buy at a
particular price over a given period of time
when other factors are held constant or other
things being equal (ceteris paribus)
d) Demand schedule and demand curve
The teacher should assist the leaner in explaining the meaning
